text:
President-elect Donald Trump has tapped Stephen Miller to serve as deputy chief of staff for policy in his new administration.

CNN, citing two sources familiar with the plans, first reported the appointment, which does not require confirmation by the Senate. Vice President-elect JD Vance said the choice of Miller, a longtime adviser who helped Trump craft immigration policy and speeches, was "another fantastic pick by the president."

During Trump’s first term, Miller advocated for the separation of migrant children from their parents as a deterrent for illegal immigration, as well as a travel ban targeting refugees and visitors coming from a handful of majority-Muslim countries.

After leaving the White House following Trump's 2020 election loss, Miller founded a conservative nonprofit group, America First Legal Foundation, that he called "the long-awaited answer to the ACLU" (American Civil Liberties Union).

Miller said in an interview with the New York Times earlier this year that "Trump will unleash the vast arsenal of federal powers to implement the most spectacular migration crackdown." As part of that, Miller said, the administration will shift from arresting specific immigrants who illegally entered the U.S. to carrying out sweeps and raids at workplaces and other public places. Because of the large number of arrests and people awaiting possible deportation, Miller said the Trump administration would build “vast holding facilities that would function as staging centers.” The new camps, Miller said, would be located “on open land in Texas near the border.”

In the same interview, Miller also said that Trump will attempt to end Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals, known by its acronym DACA. The policy, first enacted by former President Barack Obama, allows undocumented immigrants who entered the country as children to remain in the U.S. if they meet certain requirements.

Early Wednesday morning, as some U.S. news organizations were projecting that Trump had won the presidency (but before The Associated Press made its call), Miller posted on social media: “CIVILIZATION HAS BEEN SAVED.”

Trump is closing the Dept of Education (formed in 1980) and ending decades of failed education policy and overspending from D.C.

text:
We'll see, and I could be wrong, but some amorphous "band of small-government revolutionaries" is not what Trump needs to implement what is actually a pretty "big government" policy agenda (mass deportations, new healthcare reform, major immigration reform, massive tax cuts, child care policy, reducing housing costs, and major foreign policy changes).

When Trump left office in 2020, one of the takeaways from his admin was that they were too inexperienced and underprepared for D.C. Many in Trumpworld openly admitted this (that he failed vs. "the deep state") before campaign season really started. For a couple of years it seemed like their plan to fix that in a potential second term was with initiatives like Project 2025 -- essentially, policy wonking the Trump worldview and implementing it with people who had experiencing navigating D.C. Personally, I thought this was a wise reaction to the first term failures.

In the last few months of the campaign, though, something seems to have shifted. Trump distanced himself from and became disenchanted by the Heritage type conservative leader, and is now leaning into some of his surrogates as he transitions to governing; that is the Elon Musk (taking phone calls with world leaders), Vivek Ramaswamy (being talked about for a Senate appointment), and RFK Jr. types (keeps insisting he is going to have a major role in healthcare).

One initial theory that I'm operating on is that if Trump spends the first year or two of his presidency listening to people with zero government experience about how to get things done in D.C., he is once again going to waste half his term running into roadblocks, failures, and legal challenges. This would be a very similar mistake/instinct that Trump followed in 2016, which cost him pretty dearly.
